of curing a broken democratic system—what Roy terms "curative democracy." Drawing attention to an ambivalent political field that folds together authoritarian and democratic forms and ideas, Roy argues that the long 1970s were a crucial turning point in Indian politics, when democracy was suspended by the declaration of a national emergency and then subsequently restored. By tracing the crooked line that connects the ideals of curative democracy and the political outsider to the populist antipolitics and strongman authoritarian rule in present times, this book revisits democracy from India, and asks what the Indian experience tells us about the trajectory of global democratic politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthoritarianismzIndiaxHistory. 0aDemocracyzIndiaxHistory. 0aPopulismzIndiaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aAntipolitics.  aDemocratic Reform.  aIndian Emergency.  aMedia.  aNon-electoral politics.  aOutrage Politics.  aPolitical Outsiders.  aPopulism.  aPostcolonial democracy.  aStrongmen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079133440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363799340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503637993423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503637993/original  a978-3-11-079133-4  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles